Chapter 5 – Collected Proofs

(Detailed derivations of Theorems 1–5, including the ELBO derivation with Jacobian correction and the bi‑Lipschitz mapping existence proof.)

5.1 Proof of Theorem 1 (Graph as Predictive Sufficient Statistic)

Detailed derivation. The variational IB objective is:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}}(\theta) = I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - \beta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t).

Using the variational upper bound I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) \leq \mathbb{E}[\mathrm{KL}(q_\phi(\mathcal{G}_t \mid \mathbf{o}_t) \| p(\mathcal{G}_t))] and lower bound I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \geq \mathbb{E}[\log p_\psi(\mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathcal{G}_t, \mathbf{a}_t)] - H(\mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t), we obtain a tractable optimization.

At stationarity, the gradient condition \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}} = 0 implies:

\nabla_\theta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) = \beta \nabla_\theta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t).

For any alternative representation \mathbf{z}_t = g(\mathbf{o}_t), the data processing inequality gives I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \leq I(\mathbf{o}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t). The inequality in the theorem follows from the chain rule of mutual information and the IB optimality condition.

5.2 Proof of Theorem 2 (Predictive Entropy Reduction)

The entropy reduction follows from:

H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) = H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) + I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathcal{G}_{t-1} \mid \mathbf{h}_t).

For the second inequality, approximate p(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \Sigma_{\mathcal{G}}) and p(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2 I). The KL divergence is:

\mathrm{KL}(\mathcal{N}(\mu, \Sigma_{\mathcal{G}}) \| \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2 I)) = \frac{1}{2}\left( \frac{\|\mu\|^2}{\sigma^2} + \text{Tr}(\Sigma_{\mathcal{G}}/\sigma^2) - D_z - \log \det(\Sigma_{\mathcal{G}}/\sigma^2) \right).

The entropy of the prior is \frac{D_z}{2} \log(2\pi e \sigma^2). The reduction follows from the entropy power inequality.

5.3 Proof of Theorem 3 (E(3)-Equivariant Recurrent Dynamics)

Define the group action: for any g = (\mathbf{R}, \mathbf{t}) \in E(3), g \cdot \mathbf{p} = \mathbf{R} \mathbf{p} + \mathbf{t}. Node features transform as:

· Invariant scalars: g \cdot \mathbf{s} = \mathbf{s}
· Equivariant vectors: g \cdot \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{R} \mathbf{v}
· Edge distances: \|g \cdot \mathbf{p}_u - g \cdot \mathbf{p}_v\| = \|\mathbf{p}_u - \mathbf{p}_v\|

The message passing update:

\mathbf{m}_v = \sum_{u \in \mathcal{N}(v)} \phi_{\text{msg}}(\mathbf{s}_u, \mathbf{s}_v, \|\mathbf{p}_u - \mathbf{p}_v\|) \cdot \mathbf{R}_{uv} \mathbf{v}_u

is equivariant because \phi_{\text{msg}} depends only on invariants, and the rotation \mathbf{R}_{uv} transforms appropriately.

The GRU update on invariant features is invariant by construction. The parallel transport update on vector features ensures equivariance of the full state.

The symmetry-penalized loss provides a relaxation: if the model is not perfectly equivariant, the conservation error is bounded by the symmetry loss.

5.4 Proof of Theorem 4 (ANN Guarantee for Memory Retrieval)

The Johnson-Lindenstrauss lemma states that for any \epsilon \in (0, 1) and any set X of N points in \mathbb{R}^D, there exists a linear map f: \mathbb{R}^D \to \mathbb{R}^d with d = O(\epsilon^{-2} \log N) such that for all x, y \in X:

(1 - \epsilon) \|x - y\|^2 \leq \|f(x) - f(y)\|^2 \leq (1 + \epsilon) \|x - y\|^2.

For memory retrieval, let \mathcal{K} = \{\mathbf{k}_1, \ldots, \mathbf{k}_{N_m}\} be the set of memory keys. For a query \mathbf{q}, the true nearest neighbor satisfies:

\|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}^*\| \leq \|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}_i\| \quad \forall i.

In the projected space, let \tilde{\mathbf{k}} be the nearest neighbor. Then:

\|\mathbf{q} - \tilde{\mathbf{k}}\| \leq \frac{1}{1 - \epsilon} \|\Pi \mathbf{q} - \Pi \tilde{\mathbf{k}}\| \leq \frac{1}{1 - \epsilon} \|\Pi \mathbf{q} - \Pi \mathbf{k}^*\| \leq \frac{1 + \epsilon}{1 - \epsilon} \|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}^*\|.

The false retrieval probability bound follows from a union bound over all pairs of keys and the fact that \alpha-separated keys require \epsilon < \alpha / (2\|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}^*\|) for exact retrieval.

5.5 Proof of Theorem 5 (Robust Boundedness of \mathbf{h}_t)

The GRU update is:

\mathbf{z}_t = \sigma_g(W_z \mathbf{x}_t + U_z \mathbf{h}_{t-1} + \mathbf{b}_z), \quad \mathbf{r}_t = \sigma_g(W_r \mathbf{x}_t + U_r \mathbf{h}_{t-1} + \mathbf{b}_r),

\tilde{\mathbf{h}}_t = \tanh(W_h \mathbf{x}_t + U_h (\mathbf{r}_t \odot \mathbf{h}_{t-1}) + \mathbf{b}_h),

\mathbf{h}_t = (1 - \mathbf{z}_t) \odot \mathbf{h}_{t-1} + \mathbf{z}_t \odot \tilde{\mathbf{h}}_t.

Under the Lipschitz assumptions on the activation functions, we have:

\|\mathbf{h}_t\| \leq \|1 - \mathbf{z}_t\| \cdot \|\mathbf{h}_{t-1}\| + \|\mathbf{z}_t\| \cdot \|\tilde{\mathbf{h}}_t\|.

Since \|\mathbf{z}_t\| \leq \|W_z\|_2 \|\mathbf{x}_t\| + \|U_z\|_2 \|\mathbf{h}_{t-1}\| + \|\mathbf{b}_z\|, the contraction condition \|W_z\|_2, \|U_z\|_2 < 1 ensures \|\mathbf{z}_t\| < 1 for bounded \mathbf{x}_t.

By induction, \|\mathbf{h}_t\| \leq \rho^t \|\mathbf{h}_0\| + \sum_{k=0}^{t-1} \rho^k (B_u + B_r). The geometric series converges to \frac{B_u + B_r}{1 - \rho} as t \to \infty.

For perturbed updates, the perturbation is bounded by \epsilon, and the asymptotic bound increases by \frac{\epsilon}{1 - \rho}.

