Appendix A: Foundational Definitions and Notation

A.1 Probability and Information Theory

Definition A.1 (Kullback-Leibler Divergence). For two probability distributions $p$ and $q$ over a continuous random variable $X$, the KL divergence is:

\mathrm{KL}[p(X) \| q(X)] = \mathbb{E}_{X \sim p}\left[ \log \frac{p(X)}{q(X)} \right] = \int p(x) \log \frac{p(x)}{q(x)} dx.

For discrete distributions, the integral is replaced by a sum.

Definition A.2 (Mutual Information). The mutual information between random variables $X$ and $Y$ is:

I(X; Y) = \mathrm{KL}[p(X,Y) \| p(X)p(Y)] = \mathbb{E}_{p(X,Y)}\left[ \log \frac{p(X,Y)}{p(X)p(Y)} \right].

Definition A.3 (Conditional Entropy). The conditional entropy of $X$ given $Y$ is:

H(X \mid Y) = \mathbb{E}_{p(X,Y)}[-\log p(X \mid Y)].

A.2 POMDP Framework

Definition A.4 (Partially Observable Markov Decision Process). A POMDP is the tuple $(S, A, T, R, \Omega, O, \gamma)$, where:

· $S$ is the set of true (unobservable) world states,
· $A$ is the set of actions,
· $T(s' \mid s, a) = P(S_{t+1}=s' \mid S_t=s, A_t=a)$ is the transition function,
· $R(s, a)$ is the reward function,
· $\Omega(o \mid s', a) = P(O_t=o \mid S_{t+1}=s', A_t=a)$ is the observation function,
· $O$ is the observation space (multimodal, high-dimensional),
· $\gamma \in [0,1)$ is the discount factor.

Definition A.5 (Belief State). The belief state $b_t \in \Delta(S)$ (probability simplex over $S$) summarizes the history $h_t = (O_{1:t}, A_{1:t-1})$:

b_t(s) = P(S_t = s \mid h_t).

Theorem A.1 (Bayes Filter Update). The belief update (Bayes filter) is:

b_{t+1}(s') = \eta \cdot \Omega(o_{t+1} \mid s', a_t) \sum_{s} T(s' \mid s, a_t) b_t(s),

where $\eta = 1 / P(o_{t+1} \mid b_t, a_t)$ is the normalizer.

Proof. By Bayes' theorem and the Markov property:

\begin{aligned}
b_{t+1}(s') &= P(S_{t+1}=s' \mid o_{t+1}, a_t, b_t) \\
&= \frac{P(o_{t+1} \mid s', a_t, b_t) P(s' \mid a_t, b_t)}{P(o_{t+1} \mid a_t, b_t)} \\
&= \frac{\Omega(o_{t+1} \mid s', a_t) \sum_s P(s' \mid s, a_t) b_t(s)}{\sum_{s'} \Omega(o_{t+1} \mid s', a_t) \sum_s T(s' \mid s, a_t) b_t(s)}.
\end{aligned}

$\square$

