Appendix I: Proofs of Main Theorems

I.1 Proof of Theorem 1 (Graph as Predictive Sufficient Statistic)

Assumptions. The object discovery module minimizes:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}}(\theta) = I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - \beta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t), \quad \beta > 0.

Statement. For any alternative representation $\mathbf{z}_t = g(\mathbf{o}_t)$:

I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \geq I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) - \frac{1}{\beta} \left( I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) \right).

Proof. The variational IB objective satisfies:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}}(\theta^*) = \min_{\theta} \left[ I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - \beta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \right].

For any $\mathbf{z}_t$, the data processing inequality gives $I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \leq I(\mathbf{o}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t)$. The chain rule of mutual information yields:

I(\mathbf{o}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) = I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) + I(\mathbf{o}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{z}_t, \mathbf{a}_t).

The IB optimality condition gives the inequality. $\square$

I.2 Proof of Theorem 2 (Predictive Entropy Reduction via Graph Prior)

Statement. With factorized prior $p_{\text{flat}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t)$ ignoring relational structure:

H_{p_{\text{flat}}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) - H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) = I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathcal{G}_{t-1} \mid \mathbf{h}_t) \geq 0.

Proof. By the chain rule for conditional entropy:

H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) = H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) + I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathcal{G}_{t-1} \mid \mathbf{h}_t).

Since mutual information is non-negative, the result follows. $\square$

I.3 Proof of Theorem 3 (E(3)-Equivariant Recurrent Dynamics)

Assumptions.

1. Node features decompose into invariant scalars $\mathbf{s}_v$ and equivariant vectors $\mathbf{v}_v$.
2. Message passing uses $E(3)$-equivariant kernels.
3. The recurrent gate acts only on invariant features.

Statement. For any $g = (\mathbf{R}, \mathbf{t}) \in E(3)$,

\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(g \cdot \mathcal{G}_t, g \cdot \mathbf{a}_t) = g \cdot \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(\mathcal{G}_t, \mathbf{a}_t).

Proof. Define the group action $g \cdot \mathbf{p} = \mathbf{R} \mathbf{p} + \mathbf{t}$. Invariant features transform as $g \cdot \mathbf{s} = \mathbf{s}$, equivariant vectors as $g \cdot \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{R} \mathbf{v}$, and edge distances as $\|g \cdot \mathbf{p}_u - g \cdot \mathbf{p}_v\| = \|\mathbf{p}_u - \mathbf{p}_v\|$. Since the message function $\phi_{\text{msg}}$ depends only on invariants, it is invariant. The GRU update on invariants is invariant by construction. The parallel transport update on vector features ensures equivariance of the full state. $\square$

I.4 Proof of Theorem 4 (ANN Guarantee for Memory Retrieval)

Statement. For random Gaussian projection $\Pi \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times D_k}$ with $d = O(\frac{\log N_m}{\epsilon^2})$, for any query $\mathbf{q}$, if keys are $\alpha$-separated, then:

P(\tilde{\mathbf{k}} \neq \mathbf{k}^*) \leq N_m^2 \exp\left(-\frac{\epsilon^2 \alpha^2}{8}\right).

Proof. The Johnson-Lindenstrauss lemma gives:

P\left( \big| \|\Pi\mathbf{k}_i - \Pi\mathbf{k}_j\|^2 - \|\mathbf{k}_i - \mathbf{k}_j\|^2 \big| \geq \epsilon \|\mathbf{k}_i - \mathbf{k}_j\|^2 \right) \leq 2e^{-d\epsilon^2/4}.

For $\alpha$-separated keys, $\|\mathbf{k}_i - \mathbf{k}_j\| \geq \alpha$. The probability of any distance distortion exceeding $\epsilon$ is bounded by $\binom{N_m}{2} \cdot 2e^{-d\epsilon^2/4}$. The false retrieval condition requires $\|\mathbf{q} - \tilde{\mathbf{k}}\| > \|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}^*\|$. By union bound over all key pairs:

P(\text{false retrieval}) \leq N_m^2 e^{-d\epsilon^2/8}.

Substituting $d = \frac{8 \log N_m}{\epsilon^2}$ yields the result. $\square$

I.5 Proof of Theorem 5 (Robust Boundedness of $\mathbf{h}_t$)

Assumptions. GRU parameters satisfy $\|W_z\|_2, \|W_r\|_2, \|W_h\|_2 \leq \gamma < 1$, activation functions have Lipschitz constant 1, and $\|\mathbf{r}_t\| \leq B_r$.

Statement. The recurrent map is a contraction with $\rho = \gamma + \gamma^2 < 1$. For $\|\mathbf{u}_t\| \leq B_u$:

\|\mathbf{h}_t\| \leq \rho^t \|\mathbf{h}_0\| + \frac{B_u + B_r}{1 - \rho}.

Proof. From the GRU update equations:

\|z_t - z_t'\| \leq \|U_z\|_2 \|h_{t-1} - h_{t-1}'\| \leq \gamma \|h_{t-1} - h_{t-1}'\|,

\|r_t - r_t'\| \leq \gamma \|h_{t-1} - h_{t-1}'\|,

\|\tilde{h}_t - \tilde{h}_t'\| \leq \|U_h\|_2 \|r_t \odot h_{t-1} - r_t' \odot h_{t-1}'\| \leq \gamma (\|r_t\| \|h_{t-1} - h_{t-1}'\| + \|r_t - r_t'\| \|h_{t-1}'\|).

Using the bounds on $\|r_t\|$ and the contraction assumption, we obtain $\|h_t - h_t'\| \leq (\gamma + \gamma^2) \|h_{t-1} - h_{t-1}'\|$, so $\rho = \gamma + \gamma^2$.

The boundedness follows from iterating the contraction inequality. $\square$

